{
  "text": "Based on Darcy's law and estimating the pressure gradient near the crack inlet as \u0394p=l, we approximate the flux of solvent volume (per unit depth) from the hydrogel to the crack cavity as q \u00bc \u03b4k\u0394p=l, where \u03b4 is the crack inlet opening and k a material constant that controls solvent diffusivity within the hydrogel [12, 13] .W e further assume that the length scale l is proportional to the crack inlet opening, l \u00bc \u03b3\u03b4, with \u03b3 a dimensionless constant. The solvent pressure within the crack, which is approximately uniform and equal to the pressure p at the inlet [13] , exerts a load on the brittle solid. Thus, both p and the applied far-field stress \u03c3 \u221e determine the stress field in the crack region, which controls crack geometry and propagation. Then, according to linear elastic fracture mechanics, the asymptotic stress field for an edge crack of length a in polar coordinates \u00f0r; \u03b8\u00de centered at the crack tip is [CITATION_1] \u03c3\u00f0r; \u03b8\u00de",
  "correct_citation": {
